  "prompt": "How do plant cells undergo cell division without centrioles?",
  "response": "Plant cells undergo cell division through a process called mitosis, which differs from animal cell division in several key ways, particularly in the absence of centrioles. Here's how plant cells manage cell division:\n\n1. Microtubule Organization\n- Instead of centrioles, plant cells use the nuclear envelope and existing microtubules to organize the mitotic spindle\n- The spindle is formed by microtubule-organizing centers (MTOCs) located near the nucleus\n\n2. Spindle Formation Mechanism\n- Microtubules nucleate from the nuclear envelope during prophase\n- Polar microtubules extend from opposite poles of the nucleus\n- Kinetochore microtubules attach to chromosomes at their centromeres\n\n3. Cell Plate Formation\n- During cytokinesis, plants form a cell plate at the cell's center\n- Vesicles from the Golgi apparatus align and fuse to create the new cell wall\n- A phragmoplast guides this process, which is unique to plant cell division\n\n4. Chromosome Segregation\n- The process of chromosome separation is similar to animal cells\n- Spindle microtubules pull chromosomes to opposite poles of the cell\n\nThese adaptations allow plant cells to divide effectively without centrioles, demonstrating the flexibility of cellular division mechanisms across different organisms.",
